# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: distributed-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] Every read receives the most recent write or an error.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] Consistency means that all clients see the same data at the same time, no matter which node they connect to.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] This is the definition of availability in CAP theorem as defined by Gilbert and Lynch.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] The system continues to operate despite an arbitrary number of messages being dropped (or delayed) by the network between nodes.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] Thus, if there is a network partition, one has to choose between consistency or availability.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] During times of normal operations, a data store covers all three.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] No distributed system is safe from network failures, thus network partitioning generally has to be tolerated.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] In the presence of a partition, one is then left with two options: consistency or availability.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] When choosing consistency over availability, the system will return an error or a time out if particular information cannot be guaranteed to be up to date due to network partitioning.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] When choosing availability over consistency, the system will always process the query and try to return the most recent available version of the information, even if it cannot guarantee it is up to date due to network partitioning.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] In the absence of a network partition, both availability and consistency can be satisfied.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] CouchDB, Cassandra, and ScyllaDB are examples of AP databases.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] There are no NoSQL databases one would classify as CA.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] Most modern distributed databases offer configuration options for both consistency and availability.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] Some cloud services choose strong consistency but use worldwide private fiber networks and GPS clock synchronization to minimize the frequency of network partitions.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] Finally, consistent shared-nothing architectures may use techniques such as geographic sharding to maintain availability of data owned by the queried node, but without being available for arbitrary requests during a network partition.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] According to computer scientist Eric Brewer of the University of California, Berkeley, the theorem first appeared in autumn 1998.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] It was published as the CAP principle in 1999 and presented as a conjecture by Brewer at the 2000 Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC).
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] In 2002, Seth Gilbert and Nancy Lynch of MIT published a formal proof of Brewer's conjecture, rendering it a theorem.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] In 2012, Brewer clarified some of his positions, including why the often-used "two out of three" concept can be somewhat misleading because system designers only need to sacrifice consistency or availability in the presence of partitions; partition management and recovery techniques exist.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] Brewer also noted the different definition of consistency used in the CAP theorem relative to the definition used in ACID.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] A similar theorem stating the trade-off between consistency and availability in distributed systems had been published by Birman and Friedman in 1996.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] Birman and Friedman's result had restricted this lower bound to non-commuting operations.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] The PACELC theorem, introduced in 2010, builds on CAP by stating that even in the absence of partitioning, there is another trade-off between latency and consistency.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] PACELC means, if partition (P) happens, the trade-off is between availability (A) and consistency (C); Else (E), the trade-off is between latency (L) and consistency (C).
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] Some experts like Marc Brooker argue that the CAP theorem is particularly relevant in intermittently connected environments, such as those related to the Internet of Things (IoT) and mobile applications.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] In these contexts, devices may become partitioned due to challenging physical conditions, such as power outages or when entering confined spaces like elevators.
[src:distributed-systems/cap-theorem] For distributed systems, such as cloud applications, it is more appropriate to use the PACELC theorem, which is more comprehensive and considers trade-offs such as latency and consistency even in the absence of network partitions.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Consistency models are used in distributed systems like distributed shared memory systems or distributed data stores (such as filesystems, databases, optimistic replication systems or web caching).
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Consistency is different from coherence, which occurs in systems that are cached or cache-less, and is consistency of data with respect to all processors.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Coherence deals with maintaining a global order in which writes to a single location or single variable are seen by all processors.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Consistency deals with the ordering of operations to multiple locations with respect to all processors.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The consistency model determines whether client B will definitely see the write performed by client A, will definitely not, or cannot depend on seeing the write.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Consistency models define rules for the apparent order and visibility of updates, and are on a continuum with tradeoffs.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] There are two methods to define and categorize consistency models; issue and view.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Issue method describes the restrictions that define how a process can issue operations.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] For example, a consistency model can define that a process is not allowed to issue an operation until all previously issued operations are completed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Different consistency models enforce different conditions.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] One consistency model can be considered stronger than another if it requires all conditions of that model and more.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In other words, a model with fewer constraints is considered a weaker consistency model.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] These models define how the hardware needs to be laid out and at a high-level, how the programmer must code.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The chosen model also affects how the compiler can re-order instructions.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Generally, if control dependencies between instructions and if writes to same location are ordered, then the compiler can reorder as required.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] However, with the models described below, some may allow writes before loads to be reordered while some may not.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Strict consistency is the strongest consistency model.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Under this model, a write to a variable by any processor needs to be seen instantaneously by all processors.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The strict model diagram and non-strict model diagrams describe the time constraint – instantaneous.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] It can be better understood as though a global clock is present in which every write should be reflected in all processor caches by the end of that clock period.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The next operation must happen only in the next clock period.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In the following diagram, P means "process" and the global clock's value is represented in the Sequence column.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In this model, the programmer's expected result will be received every time.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Its practical relevance is restricted to a thought experiment and formalism, because instantaneous message exchange is impossible.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] It doesn't help in answering the question of conflict resolution in concurrent writes to the same data item, because it assumes concurrent writes to be impossible.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The sequential consistency model was proposed by Lamport (1979).
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] It is a weaker memory model than strict consistency model.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A write to a variable does not have to be seen instantaneously, however, writes to variables by different processors have to be seen in the same order by all processors.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In sequential consistency, there is no notion of time or most recent write operations.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] There are some operations interleaving that is the same for all processes.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A process can see the write operations of all processes but it can just see its own read operations.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Program order within each processor and sequential ordering of operations between processors should be maintained.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In order to preserve sequential order of execution between processors, all operations must appear to execute instantaneously or atomically with respect to every other processor.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] These operations need only "appear" to be completed because it is physically impossible to send information instantaneously.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] For instance, in a system utilizing a single globally shared bus, once a bus line is posted with information, it is guaranteed that all processors will see the information at the same instant.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Thus, passing the information to the bus line completes the execution with respect to all processors and has appeared to have been executed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Cache-less architectures or cached architectures with interconnect networks that are not instantaneous can contain a slow path between processors and memories.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] These slow paths can result in sequential inconsistency, because some memories receive the broadcast data faster than others.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Sequential consistency can produce non-deterministic results.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] This is because the sequence of sequential operations between processors can be different during different runs of the program.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] All memory operations need to happen in the program order.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Linearizability (also known as atomic consistency or atomic memory) can be defined as sequential consistency with a real-time constraint, by considering a begin time and end time for each operation.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] An execution is linearizable if each operation taking place in linearizable order by placing a point between its begin time and its end time and guarantees sequential consistency.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Verifying sequential consistency through model checking is undecidable in general, even for finite-state cache coherence protocols.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Causal consistency defined by Hutto and Ahamad, 1990, is a weakening of the sequential consistency model by categorizing events into those causally related and those that are not.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] It defines that only write operations that are causally related, need to be seen in the same order by all processes.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] For example, if an event b takes effect from an earlier event a, the causal consistency guarantees that all processes see event b after event a.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] This model relaxes sequential consistency on concurrent writes by a processor and on writes that are not causally related.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Two writes can become causally related if one write to a variable is dependent on a previous write to any variable if the processor doing the second write has just read the first write.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The two writes could have been done by the same processor or by different processors.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] As in sequential consistency, reads do not need to reflect changes instantaneously, however, they need to reflect all changes to a variable sequentially.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] W(x)2 happens after W(x)1 due to the read made by P2 to x before W(x)2, hence this example is *causally consistent* under Hutto and Ahamad's definition (although not under Tanenbaum et al.'s, because W(x)2 and W(x)3 are not seen in the same order for all processes).
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] However R(x)2 and R(x)3 happen in a different order on P3 and P4, hence this example is *sequentially inconsistent*.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In order for consistency in data to be maintained and to attain scalable processor systems where every processor has its own memory, the processor consistency model was derived.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] All processors need to be consistent in the order in which they see writes done by one processor and in the way they see writes by different processors to the same location (coherence is maintained).
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] However, they do not need to be consistent when the writes are by different processors to different locations.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Every write operation can be divided into several sub-writes to all memories.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A read from one such memory can happen before the write to this memory completes.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Thus, a processor under PC can execute a younger load when an older store needs to be stalled.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Read before write, read after read and write before write ordering is still preserved in this model.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The processor consistency model is similar to the PRAM consistency model with a stronger condition that defines all writes to the same memory location must be seen in the same sequential order by all other processes.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Processor consistency is weaker than sequential consistency but stronger than the PRAM consistency model.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The Stanford DASH multiprocessor system implements a variation of processor consistency which is incomparable (neither weaker nor stronger) to Goodman's definitions.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] All processors need to be consistent in the order in which they see writes by one processor and in the way they see writes by different processors to the same location.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Pipelined RAM consistency (PRAM consistency) was presented by Lipton and Sandberg in 1988 as one of the first described consistency models.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Due to its informal definition, there are in fact at least two subtly different implementations, one by Ahamad et al. and one by Mosberger.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In PRAM consistency, all processes view the operations of a single process in the same order that they were issued by that process, while operations issued by different processes can be viewed in different order from different processes.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] PRAM consistency is weaker than processor consistency.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] PRAM relaxes the need to maintain coherence to a location across all its processors.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Here, reads to any variable can be executed before writes in a processor.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Cache consistency requires that all write operations to the same memory location are performed in some sequential order.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Cache consistency is weaker than processor consistency and incomparable with PRAM consistency.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In slow consistency, if a process reads a value previously written to a memory location, it cannot subsequently read any earlier value from that location.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Writes performed by a process are immediately visible to that process.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Slow consistency is a weaker model than PRAM and cache consistency.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Hutto, Phillip W., and Mustaque Ahamad (1990) illustrate that by appropriate programming, slow memory (consistency) can be expressive and efficient.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] They mention that slow memory has two valuable properties; locality and supporting reduction from atomic memory.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] They propose two algorithms to present the expressiveness of slow memory.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] These 4 consistency models were proposed in a 1994 paper.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] They focus on guarantees in the situation where only a single user or application is making data modifications.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] If a process reads the value of a data item x, any successive read operation on x by that process will always return that same value or a more recent value.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A write operation by a process on a data item X is completed before any successive write operation on X by the same process.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A value written by a process on a data item X will always be available to a successive read operation performed by the same process on data item X.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A write operation by a process on a data item x following a previous read operation on x by the same process is guaranteed to take place on the same or a more recent value of x that was read.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The following models require specific synchronization by programmers.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Weak ordering classifies memory operations into two categories: *data operations* and *synchronization operations*.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] To enforce program order, a programmer needs to find at least one synchronisation operation in a program.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Synchronization operations signal the processor to make sure it has completed and seen all previous operations done by all processors.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Program order and atomicity is maintained only on synchronisation operations and not on all reads and writes.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] This was derived from the understanding that certain memory operations – such as those conducted in a critical section - need not be seen by all processors until after all operations in the critical section are completed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] It assumes reordering memory operations to data regions between synchronisation operations does not affect the outcome of the program.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] This exploits the fact that programs written to be executed on a multi-processor system contain the required synchronization to make sure that data races do not occur and SC outcomes are produced always.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Once these requirements are met, all other "data" operations can be reordered.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The way this works is that a counter tracks the number of data operations and until this counter becomes zero, the synchronisation operation isn't issued.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Furthermore, no more data operations are issued unless all the previous synchronisations are completed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Memory operations in between two synchronisation variables can be overlapped and reordered without affecting the correctness of the program.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] This model ensures that write atomicity is always maintained, therefore no additional safety net is required for weak ordering.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In order to maintain weak ordering, write operations prior to a synchronization operation must be globally performed before the synchronization operation.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Operations present after a synchronization operation should also be performed only after the synchronization operation completes.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Therefore, accesses to synchronization variables is sequentially consistent and any read or write should be performed only after previous synchronization operations have completed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] There is high reliance on explicit synchronization in the program.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] For weak ordering models, the programmer must use atomic locking instructions such as test-and-set, fetch-and-op, store conditional, load linked or must label synchronization variables or use fences.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The release consistency model relaxes the weak consistency model by distinguishing the entrance synchronization operation from the exit synchronization operation.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Under weak ordering, when a synchronization operation is to be seen, all operations in all processors need to be visible before the synchronization operation is done and the processor proceeds.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] However, under the release consistency model, during the entry to a critical section, termed as "acquire", all operations with respect to the local memory variables need to be completed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] During the exit, termed as "release", all changes made by the local processor should be propagated to all other processors.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The acquire operation is a load/read that is performed to access the critical section.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A release operation is a store/write performed to allow other processors to use the shared variables.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Among synchronization variables, sequential consistency or processor consistency can be maintained.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Using SC, all competing synchronization variables should be processed in order.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] However, with PC, a pair of competing variables need to only follow this order.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Younger acquires can be allowed to happen before older releases.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] There are two types of release consistency, release consistency with sequential consistency (RCsc) and release consistency with processor consistency (RCpc).
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The latter type denotes which type of consistency is applied to those operations nominated below as special.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] There are special (cf. ordinary) memory operations, themselves consisting of two classes of operations: *sync* or *nsync* operations.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The latter are operations not used for synchronisation; the former are, and consist of *acquire* and *release* operations.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] An acquire is effectively a read memory operation used to obtain access to a certain set of shared locations.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Release, on the other hand, is a write operation that is performed for granting permission to access the shared locations.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Note: the above notation A → B, implies that if the operation A precedes B in the program order, then program order is enforced.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] This is a variant of the release consistency model.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] It also requires the use of *acquire* and *release* instructions to explicitly state an entry or exit to a critical section.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] However, under entry consistency, every shared variable is assigned a synchronization variable specific to it.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] This way, only when the acquire is to variable x, all operations related to x need to be completed with respect to that processor.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] This allows concurrent operations of different critical sections of different shared variables to occur.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Concurrency cannot be seen for critical operations on the same shared variable.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Such a consistency model will be useful when different matrix elements can be processed at the same time.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In local consistency, each process performs its own operations in the order defined by its program.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] There is no constraint on the ordering in which the write operations of other processes appear to be performed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Local consistency is the weakest consistency model in shared memory systems.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In general consistency, all the copies of a memory location are eventually identical after all processes' writes are completed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] An eventual consistency is a weak consistency model in a system with the lack of simultaneous updates.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] It defines that if no update takes a very long time, all replicas eventually become consistent.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Some different consistency models can be defined by relaxing one or more requirements in sequential consistency called relaxed consistency models.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] These consistency models do not provide memory consistency at the hardware level.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In fact, the programmers are responsible for implementing the memory consistency by applying synchronization techniques.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The above models are classified based on four criteria and are detailed further.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] One way to categorize the relaxed consistency is to define which sequential consistency requirements are relaxed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] We can have less strict models by relaxing either program order or write atomicity requirements defined by Adve and Gharachorloo, 1996.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Program order guarantees that each process issues a memory request ordered by its program and write atomicity defines that memory requests are serviced based on the order of a single FIFO queue.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In relaxing program order, any or all the ordering of operation pairs, write-after-write, read-after-write, or read/write-after-read, can be relaxed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In the relaxed write atomicity model, a process can view its own writes before any other processors.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A synchronizing model can be defined by dividing the memory accesses into two groups and assigning different consistency restrictions to each group considering that one group can have a weak consistency model while the other one needs a more restrictive consistency model.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In contrast, a non-synchronizing model assigns the same consistency model to the memory access types.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Issue method provides sequential consistency simulation by defining the restrictions for processes to issue memory operations.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Whereas, view method describes the visibility restrictions on the events order for processes.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Some consistency models are more restrictive than others.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In other words, strict consistency models enforce more constraints as consistency requirements.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The strength of a model can be defined by the program order or atomicity relaxations and the strength of models can also be compared.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Some models are directly related if they apply the same relaxations or more.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] On the other hand, the models that relax different requirements are not directly related.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Sequential consistency has two requirements, program order and write atomicity.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Different relaxed consistency models can be obtained by relaxing these requirements.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] This is done so that, along with relaxed constraints, the performance increases, but the programmer is responsible for implementing the memory consistency by applying synchronisation techniques and must have a good understanding of the hardware.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] An approach to improving the performance at the hardware level is by relaxing the PO of a write followed by a read which effectively hides the latency of write operations.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The optimisation this type of relaxation relies on is that it allows the subsequent reads to be in a relaxed order with respect to the previous writes from the processor.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Because of this relaxation some programs like XXX may fail to give SC results because of this relaxation.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Whereas, programs like YYY are still expected to give consistent results because of the enforcement of the remaining program order constraints.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The IBM 370 model is the strictest model.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A read can be complete before an earlier write to a different address, but it is prohibited from returning the value of the write unless all the processors have seen the write.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The SPARC V8 total store ordering model (TSO) model partially relaxes the IBM 370 Model, it allows a read to return the value of its own processor's write with respect to other writes to the same location i.e. it returns the value of its own write before others see it.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Similar to the previous model, this cannot return the value of write unless all the processors have seen the write.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The processor consistency model (PC) is the most relaxed of the three models and relaxes both the constraints such that a read can complete before an earlier write even before it is made visible to other processors.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In Example A, the result is possible only in IBM 370 because read(A) is not issued until the write(A) in that processor is completed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] On the other hand, this result is possible in TSO and PC because they allow the reads of the flags before the writes of the flags in a single processor.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In Example B the result is possible only with PC as it allows P2 to return the value of a write even before it is visible to P3.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] This won't be possible in the other two models.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] To ensure sequential consistency in the above models, safety nets or fences are used to manually enforce the constraint.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The IBM370 model has some specialised *serialisation instructions* which are manually placed between operations.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] These instructions can consist of memory instructions or non-memory instructions such as branches.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] On the other hand, the TSO and PC models do not provide safety nets, but the programmers can still use read-modify-write operations to make it appear like the program order is still maintained between a write and a following read.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In case of TSO, PO appears to be maintained if the R or W which is already a part of a R-modify-W is replaced by a R-modify-W, this requires the W in the R-modify-W is a ‘dummy’ that returns the read value.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Similarly for PC, PO seems to be maintained if the read is replaced by a write or is already a part of R-modify-W.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] However, compiler optimisations cannot be done after exercising this relaxation alone.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Compiler optimisations require the full flexibility of reordering any two operations in the PO, so the ability to reorder a write with respect to a read is not sufficiently helpful in this case.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Some models relax the program order even further by relaxing even the ordering constraints between writes to different locations.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The SPARC V8 partial store ordering model (PSO) is the only example of such a model.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The ability to pipeline and overlap writes to different locations from the same processor is the key hardware optimisation enabled by PSO.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] PSO is similar to TSO in terms of atomicity requirements, in that it allows a processor to read the value of its own write and prevents other processors from reading another processor's write before the write is visible to all other processors.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Program order between two writes is maintained by PSO using an explicit STBAR instruction.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The STBAR is inserted in a write buffer in implementations with FIFO write buffers.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A counter is used to determine when all the writes before the STBAR instruction have been completed, which triggers a write to the memory system to increment the counter.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A write acknowledgement decrements the counter, and when the counter becomes 0, it signifies that all the previous writes are completed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In the examples A and B, PSO allows both these non-sequentially consistent results.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The safety net that PSO provides is similar to TSO's, it imposes program order from a write to a read and enforces write atomicity.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Similar to the previous models, the relaxations allowed by PSO are not sufficiently flexible to be useful for compiler optimisation, which requires a much more flexible optimisation.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In some models, all operations to different locations are relaxed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A read or write may be reordered with respect to a different read or write in a different location.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The *weak ordering* may be classified under this category and two types of release consistency models (RCsc and RCpc) also come under this model.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Three commercial architectures are also proposed under this category of relaxation: the Digital Alpha, SPARC V9 relaxed memory order (RMO), and IBM PowerPC models.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] These three commercial architectures exhibit explicit fence instructions as their safety nets.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The Alpha model provides two types of fence instructions, *memory barrier* (MB) and *write memory barrier* (WMB).
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The MB operation can be used to maintain program order of any memory operation before the MB with a memory operation after the barrier.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Similarly, the WMB maintains program order only among writes.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The SPARC V9 RMO model provides a MEMBAR instruction which can be customised to order previous reads and writes with respect to future read and write operations.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] There is no need for using read-modify-writes to achieve this order because the MEMBAR instruction can be used to order a write with respect to a succeeding read.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The PowerPC model uses a single fence instruction called the SYNC instruction.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] It is similar to the MB instruction, but with a little exception that reads can occur out of program order even if a SYNC is placed between two reads to the same location.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] This model also differs from Alpha and RMO in terms of atomicity.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] It allows a write to be seen earlier than a read's completion.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A combination of read modify write operations may be required to make an illusion of write atomicity.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] RMO and PowerPC allow reordering of reads to the same location.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] These models violate sequential order in examples A and B.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] An additional relaxation allowed in these models is that memory operations following a read operation can be overlapped and reordered with respect to the read.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Alpha and RMO allow a read to return the value of another processor's early write.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] From a programmer's perspective these models must maintain the illusion of write atomicity even though they allow the processor to read its own write early.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Transactional memory model is the combination of cache coherency and memory consistency models as a communication model for shared memory systems supported by software or hardware; a transactional memory model provides both memory consistency and cache coherency.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A transaction is a sequence of operations executed by a process that transforms data from one consistent state to another.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A transaction either commits when there is no conflict or aborts.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In commits, all changes are visible to all other processes when a transaction is completed, while aborts discard all changes.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Compared to relaxed consistency models, a transactional model is easier to use and can provide higher performance than a sequential consistency model.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Several other consistency models have been conceived to express restrictions with respect to ordering or visibility of operations, or to deal with specific fault assumptions.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Tanenbaum et al., 2007 defines two main reasons for replicating; reliability and performance.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Reliability can be achieved in a replicated file system by switching to another replica in the case of the current replica failure.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The replication also protects data from being corrupted by providing multiple copies of data on different replicas.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] It also improves the performance by dividing the work.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] While replication can improve performance and reliability, it can cause consistency problems between multiple copies of data.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The multiple copies are consistent if a read operation returns the same value from all copies and a write operation as a single atomic operation (transaction) updates all copies before any other operation takes place.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Tanenbaum, Andrew, & Maarten Van Steen, 2007 refer to this type of consistency as **tight consistency** provided by synchronous replication.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] However, applying global synchronizations to keep all copies consistent is costly.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] One way to decrease the cost of global synchronization and improve the performance can be weakening the consistency restrictions.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Tanenbaum et al., 2007 defines the **consistency model** as a contract between the software (processes) and memory implementation (data store).
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] This model guarantees that if the software follows certain rules, the memory works correctly.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Since, in a system without a global clock, defining the last operation among writes is difficult, some restrictions can be applied on the values that can be returned by a read operation.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The goal of data-centric consistency models is to provide a consistent view on a data store where processes may carry out concurrent updates.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Some consistency models such as sequential and also causal consistency models deal with the order of operations on shared replicated data in order to provide consistency.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In these models, all replicas must agree on a consistent global ordering of updates.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In grouping operation, accesses to the synchronization variables are sequentially consistent.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A process is allowed to access a synchronization variable that all previous writes have been completed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In other words, accesses to synchronization variables are not permitted until all operations on the synchronization variables are completely performed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In distributed systems, maintaining sequential consistency in order to control the concurrent operations is essential.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In some special data stores without simultaneous updates, client-centric consistency models can deal with inconsistencies in a less costly way.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The implementation of a consistency model is defined by a consistency protocol.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Tanenbaum et al., 2007 illustrates some consistency protocols for data-centric models.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Continuous consistency introduced by Yu and Vahdat (2000).
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In this model, the consistency semantics of an application is described by using conits in the application.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Since the consistency requirements can differ based on application semantics, Yu and Vahdat (2000) believe that a predefined uniform consistency model may not be an appropriate approach.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The application should specify the consistency requirements that satisfy the application semantics.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In this model, an application specifies each consistency requirement as a conit (abbreviation of consistency units).
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A conit can be a physical or logical consistency and is used to measure the consistency.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Tanenbaum et al., 2007 describes the notion of a conit by giving an example.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] There are three inconsistencies that can be tolerated by applications.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Numerical deviation bounds the difference between the conit value and the relative value of the last update.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A weight can be assigned to the writes which defines the importance of the writes in a specific application.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The total weights of unseen writes for a conit can be defined as a numerical deviation in an application.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] There are two different types of numerical deviation; absolute and relative numerical deviation.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Ordering deviation is the discrepancy between the local order of writes in a replica and their relative ordering in the eventual final image.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Staleness deviation defines the validity of the oldest write by bounding the difference between the current time and the time of the oldest write on a conit not seen locally.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Each server has a local queue of uncertain write that is required an actual order to be determined and applied on a conit.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The maximal length of uncertain writes queue is the bound of ordering deviation.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] When the number of writes exceeds the limit, instead of accepting new submitted write, the server will attempt to commit uncertain writes by communicating with other servers based on the order that writes should be executed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] If all three deviation bounds are set to zero, the continuous consistency model is the strong consistency.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Primary-based protocols can be considered as a class of consistency protocols that are simpler to implement.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] For instance, sequential ordering is a popular consistency model when consistent ordering of operations is considered.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The sequential ordering can be determined as primary-based protocol.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In these protocols, there is an associated primary for each data item in a data store to coordinate write operations on that data item.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In the simplest primary-based protocol that supports replication, also known as primary-backup protocol, write operations are forwarded to a single server and read operations can be performed locally.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] gives an example of a primary-backup protocol.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The diagram of primary-backup protocol shows an example of this protocol.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] When a client requests a write, the write request is forwarded to a primary server.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The primary server sends request to backups to perform the update.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The server then receives the update acknowledgement from all backups and sends the acknowledgement of completion of writes to the client.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Any client can read the last available update locally.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The trade-off of this protocol is that a client who sends the update request might have to wait so long to get the acknowledgement in order to continue.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] This problem can be solved by performing the updates locally, and then asking other backups to perform their updates.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The non-blocking primary-backup protocol does not guarantee the consistency of update on all backup servers.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In the primary-backup protocol, all processes will see the same order of write operations since this protocol orders all incoming writes based on a globally unique time.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Blocking protocols guarantee that processes view the result of the last write operation.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In primary-based local-write protocols, primary copy moves between processes willing to perform an update.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] To update a data item, a process first moves it to its location.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] As a result, in this approach, successive write operations can be performed locally while each process can read their local copy of data items.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] After the primary finishes its update, the update is forwarded to other replicas and all perform the update locally.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] This non-blocking approach can lead to an improvement.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The diagram of the local-write protocol depicts the local-write approach in primary-based protocols.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A process requests a write operation in a data item x.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The current server is considered as the new primary for a data item x.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The write operation is performed and when the request is finished, the primary sends an update request to other backup servers.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Each backup sends an acknowledgment to the primary after finishing the update operation.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In replicated-write protocols, unlike the primary-based protocol, all updates are carried out to all replicas.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In active replication, there is a process associated with each replica to perform the write operation.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In other words, updates are sent to each replica in the form of an operation in order to be executed.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] All updates need to be performed in the same order in all replicas.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] As a result, a totally-ordered multicast mechanism is required.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] There is a scalability issue in implementing such a multicasting mechanism in large distributed systems.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] There is another approach in which each operation is sent to a central coordinator (sequencer).
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The coordinator first assigns a sequence number to each operation and then forwards the operation to all replicas.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Second approach cannot also solve the scalability problem.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Voting can be another approach in replicated-write protocols.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In this approach, a client requests and receives permission from multiple servers in order to read and write a replicated data.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] As an example, suppose in a distributed file system, a file is replicated on N servers.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] To update a file, a client must send a request to at least N/2 + 1 in order to make their agreement to perform an update.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] After the agreement, changes are applied on the file and a new version number is assigned to the updated file.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Similarly, for reading replicated file, a client sends a request to N/2 + 1 servers in order to receive the associated version number from those servers.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Read operation is completed if all received version numbers are the most recent version.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In a replicated file system, a cache-coherence protocol provides the cache consistency while caches are generally controlled by clients.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In many approaches, cache consistency is provided by the underlying hardware.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Some other approaches in middleware-based distributed systems apply software-based solutions to provide the cache consistency.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Cache consistency models can differ in their coherence detection strategies that define when inconsistencies occur.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] There are two approaches to detect the inconsistency; static and dynamic solutions.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In the static solution, a compiler determines which variables can cause the cache inconsistency.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] So, the compiler enforces an instruction in order to avoid the inconsistency problem.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In the dynamic solution, the server checks for inconsistencies at run time to control the consistency of the cached data that has changed after it was cached.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] The coherence enforcement strategy is another cache-coherence protocol.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] It defines *how* to provide the consistency in caches by using the copies located on the server.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] One way to keep the data consistent is to never cache the shared data.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] A server can keep the data and apply some consistency protocol such as primary-based protocols to ensure the consistency of shared data.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In this solution, only private data can be cached by clients.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In the case that shared data is cached, there are two approaches in order to enforce the cache coherence.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In the first approach, when a shared data is updated, the server forwards invalidation to all caches.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] In the second approach, an update is propagated.
[src:distributed-systems/consistency-model] Most caching systems apply these two approaches or dynamically choose between them.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:distributed-systems/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:distributed-systems/eventual-consistency] Eventually-consistent services are often classified as providing BASE semantics (basically-available, soft-state, eventual consistency), in contrast to traditional ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability).
[src:distributed-systems/eventual-consistency] Eventual consistency faces criticism for adding complexity to distributed software applications.
[src:distributed-systems/eventual-consistency] This complexity arises because eventual consistency provides only a liveness guarantee (ensuring reads eventually return the same value) without safety guarantees—allowing any intermediate value before convergence.
[src:distributed-systems/eventual-consistency] Application developers find this challenging because it differs from single-threaded programming, where variables reliably return their assigned values immediately.
[src:distributed-systems/eventual-consistency] With weak consistency guarantees, developers must carefully consider these limitations, as incorrect assumptions about consistency levels can lead to subtle bugs that only surface during network failures or high concurrency.
[src:distributed-systems/eventual-consistency] In order to ensure replica convergence, a system must reconcile differences between multiple copies of distributed data.
[src:distributed-systems/eventual-consistency] The most appropriate approach to reconciliation depends on the application.
[src:distributed-systems/eventual-consistency] A widespread approach is "last writer wins".
[src:distributed-systems/eventual-consistency] Another is to invoke a user-specified conflict handler.
[src:distributed-systems/eventual-consistency] Timestamps and vector clocks are often used to detect concurrency between updates.
[src:distributed-systems/eventual-consistency] Some people use "first writer wins" in situations where "last writer wins" is unacceptable.
[src:distributed-systems/eventual-consistency] Whereas eventual consistency is only a liveness guarantee (updates will be observed eventually), **strong eventual consistency** (SEC) adds the safety guarantee that any two nodes that have received the same (unordered) set of updates will be in the same state.
[src:distributed-systems/eventual-consistency] A common approach to ensure SEC is conflict-free replicated data types.
[src:distributed-systems/fallacies-of-distributed-computing] The **fallacies of distributed computing** are a set of assertions made by L.
[src:distributed-systems/fallacies-of-distributed-computing] Peter Deutsch and others at Sun Microsystems describing false assumptions that programmers new to distributed applications invariably make.
[src:distributed-systems/fallacies-of-distributed-computing] Ignorance of network latency, and of the packet loss it can cause, induces application- and transport-layer developers to allow unbounded traffic, greatly increasing dropped packets and wasting bandwidth.
[src:distributed-systems/fallacies-of-distributed-computing] Ignorance of bandwidth limits on the part of traffic senders can result in bottlenecks.
[src:distributed-systems/fallacies-of-distributed-computing] Complacency regarding network security results in being blindsided by malicious users and programs that continually adapt to security measures.
[src:distributed-systems/fallacies-of-distributed-computing] Changes in network topology can have effects on both bandwidth and latency issues, and therefore can have similar problems.
[src:distributed-systems/fallacies-of-distributed-computing] Multiple administrators, as with subnets for rival companies, may institute conflicting policies of which senders of network traffic must be aware in order to complete their desired paths.
[src:distributed-systems/fallacies-of-distributed-computing] The "hidden" costs of building and maintaining a network or subnet are non-negligible and must consequently be noted in budgets to avoid vast shortfalls.
[src:distributed-systems/fallacies-of-distributed-computing] If a system assumes a homogeneous network, then it can lead to the same problems that result from the first three fallacies.
[src:distributed-systems/fallacies-of-distributed-computing] The list of fallacies originated at Sun Microsystems.
[src:distributed-systems/fallacies-of-distributed-computing] Peter Deutsch, one of the original Sun "Fellows", first created a list of seven fallacies in 1994; incorporating four fallacies Bill Joy and Dave Lyon had already identified in "The Fallacies of Networked Computing".
[src:distributed-systems/fallacies-of-distributed-computing] Around 1997, James Gosling, another Sun Fellow and the inventor of Java, added the eighth fallacy.
[src:distributed-systems/fallacies-of-distributed-computing] In an episode of "Software Engineering Radio" Peter Deutsch added a ninth fallacy: "It's really an expansion of number 4.
[src:distributed-systems/fallacies-of-distributed-computing] It extends beyond the boundaries of the physical network. ...
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] A **gossip protocol** or **epidemic protocol** is a procedure or process of computer peer-to-peer communication that is based on the way epidemics spread.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] Some distributed systems use peer-to-peer gossip to ensure that data is disseminated to all members of a group.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] Some ad-hoc networks have no central registry and the only way to spread common data is to rely on each member to pass it along to their neighbors.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] The concept of *gossip communication* can be illustrated by the analogy of office workers spreading rumors.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] Let's say each hour the office workers congregate around the water cooler.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] Each employee pairs off with another, chosen at random, and shares the latest gossip.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] At the start of the day, Dave starts a new rumor: he comments to Bob that he believes that Charlie dyes his mustache.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] At the next meeting, Bob tells Alice, while Dave repeats the idea to Eve.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] After each water cooler rendezvous, the number of individuals who have heard the rumor roughly doubles (though this doesn't account for gossiping twice to the same person; perhaps Dave tries to tell the story to Frank, only to find that Frank already heard it from Alice).
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] Computer systems typically implement this type of protocol with a form of random "peer selection": with a given frequency, each machine picks another machine at random and shares any rumors.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] There are probably hundreds of variants of specific gossip-like protocols because each use-scenario is likely to be customized to the organization's specific needs.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] *Background data dissemination protocols* continuously gossip about information associated with the participating nodes.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] Typically, propagation latency isn't a concern, perhaps because the information in question changes slowly or there is no significant penalty for acting upon slightly stale data.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] Many protocols that predate the earliest use of the term "gossip" fall within this rather inclusive definition.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] For example, Internet routing protocols often use gossip-like information exchanges.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] A gossip substrate can be used to implement a standard routed network: nodes "gossip" about traditional point-to-point messages, effectively pushing traffic through the gossip layer.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] Bandwidth permitting, this implies that a gossip system can potentially support any classic protocol or implement any classical distributed service.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] However, such a broadly inclusive interpretation is rarely intended.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] More typically gossip protocols are those that specifically run in a regular, periodic, relatively lazy, symmetric and decentralized manner; the high degree of symmetry among nodes is particularly characteristic.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] Thus, while one could run a 2-phase commit protocol over a gossip substrate, doing so would be at odds with the spirit, if not the wording, of the definition.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] The term *convergently consistent* is sometimes used to describe protocols that achieve exponentially rapid spread of information.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] For this purpose, a protocol must propagate any new information to all nodes that will be affected by the information within time logarithmic in the size of the system (the "mixing time" must be logarithmic in system size).
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] Suppose that we want to find the object that most closely matches some search pattern, within a network of unknown size, but where the computers are linked to one another and where each machine is running a small *agent* program that implements a gossip protocol.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] If the messages might get large (for example, if many searches are active all at the same time), a size limit should be introduced.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] Also, searches should "age out" of the network.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] It follows that within logarithmic time in the size of the network (the number of agents), any new search string will have reached all agents.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] Within an additional delay of the same approximate length, every agent will learn where the best match can be found.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] In particular, the agent that started the search will have found the best match.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] For example, in a network with 25,000 machines, we can find the best match after about 30 rounds of gossip: 15 to spread the search string and 15 more to discover the best match.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] A gossip exchange could occur as often as once every tenth of a second without imposing undue load, hence this form of network search could search a big data center in about three seconds.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] In this scenario, searches might automatically age out of the network after, say, 10 seconds.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] By then, the initiator knows the answer and there is no point in further gossip about that search.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] Gossip protocols can be used to propagate information in a manner rather similar to the way that a viral infection spreads in a biological population.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] Indeed, the mathematics of epidemics are often used to model the mathematics of gossip communication.
[src:distributed-systems/gossip-protocol] The term *epidemic algorithm* is sometimes employed when describing a software system in which this kind of gossip-based information propagation is employed.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] The term was introduced by American mathematician Benjamin Peirce in 1870 in the context of elements of algebras that remain invariant when raised to a positive integer power, and literally means "(the quality of having) the same power", from *idem* + *potence* (same + power).
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] If the set E has n elements, we can partition it into k chosen fixed points and $n-k$ non-fixed points under f , and then $k^{n-k}$ is the number of different idempotent functions.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] is the total number of possible idempotent functions on the set.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] Neither idempotence nor non-idempotence is preserved under function composition.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] As an example for the former, $f(x)=x$ mod 3 and $g(x)=\max(x,5)$ are both idempotent, but $f\circ g$ is not, although $g\circ f$ happens to be.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] As an example for the latter, the negation function $\neg$ on the Boolean domain is not idempotent, but $\neg \circ \neg$ is.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] Similarly, unary negation $-(\cdot )$ of real numbers is not idempotent, but $-(\cdot )\circ -(\cdot )$ is.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] In both cases, the composition is simply the identity function, which is idempotent.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] A morphism $f:x\to x$ in a category is called *idempotent* if $f\circ f=f$ .
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] An idempotent is said to *split* if it can be written as $f=h\circ g$ for some $g:x\to y,\,h:y\to x$ with $g\circ h=\operatorname {id}$ .
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] A category is said to be idempotent complete if every idempotent splits.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] For example, ${\mathsf {Set}}$ is idempotent complete.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] This is a very useful property in many situations, as it means that an operation can be repeated or retried as often as necessary without causing unintended effects.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] With non-idempotent operations, the algorithm may have to keep track of whether the operation was already performed or not.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] A function looking up a customer's name and address in a database is typically idempotent, since this will not cause the database to change.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] Similarly, a request for changing a customer's address to XYZ is typically idempotent, because the final address will be the same no matter how many times the request is submitted.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] However, a customer request for placing an order is typically not idempotent since multiple requests will lead to multiple orders being placed.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] A request for canceling a particular order is idempotent because no matter how many requests are made the order remains canceled.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] A sequence of idempotent subroutines where at least one subroutine is different from the others, however, is not necessarily idempotent if a later subroutine in the sequence changes a value that an earlier subroutine depends on—*idempotence is not closed under sequential composition*.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] For example, suppose the initial value of a variable is 3 and there is a subroutine sequence that reads the variable, then changes it to 5, and then reads it again.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] Each step in the sequence is idempotent: both steps reading the variable have no side effects and the step changing the variable to 5 will always have the same effect no matter how many times it is executed.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] Nonetheless, executing the entire sequence once produces the output (3, 5), but executing it a second time produces the output (5, 5), so the sequence is not idempotent.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] In the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), idempotence and safety are the major attributes that separate HTTP methods.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] Of the major HTTP methods, GET, PUT, and DELETE should be implemented in an idempotent manner according to the standard, but POST doesn't need to be.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] GET retrieves the state of a resource; PUT updates the state of a resource; and DELETE deletes a resource.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] As in the example above, reading data usually has no side effects, so it is idempotent (in fact *nullipotent*).
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] Updating and deleting a given data are each usually idempotent as long as the request uniquely identifies the resource and only that resource again in the future.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] PUT and DELETE with unique identifiers reduce to the simple case of assignment to a variable of either a value or the null-value, respectively, and are idempotent for the same reason; the end result is always the same as the result of the initial execution, even if the response differs.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] Violation of the unique identification requirement in storage or deletion typically causes violation of idempotence.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] Similarly, PUT and DELETE requests with nonspecific criteria may result in different outcomes depending on the state of the system – for example, a request to delete the most recent record.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] In each case, subsequent executions will further modify the state of the system, so they are not idempotent.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] In event stream processing, idempotence refers to the ability of a system to produce the same outcome, even if the same file, event or message is received more than once.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] In a load–store architecture, instructions that might possibly cause a page fault are idempotent.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] So if a page fault occurs, the operating system can load the page from disk and then simply re-execute the faulted instruction.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] In a processor where such instructions are not idempotent, dealing with page faults is much more complex.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] When reformatting output, pretty-printing is expected to be idempotent.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] In other words, if the output is already "pretty", there should be nothing to do for the pretty-printer.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] In service-oriented architecture (SOA), a multiple-step orchestration process composed entirely of idempotent steps can be replayed without side-effects if any part of that process fails.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] Many operations that are idempotent often have ways to "resume" a process if it is interrupted – ways that finish much faster than starting all over from the beginning.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] For example, resuming a file transfer, synchronizing files, creating a software build, installing an application and all of its dependencies with a package manager, etc.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] Applied examples that many people could encounter in their day-to-day lives include elevator call buttons and crosswalk buttons.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] The initial activation of the button moves the system into a requesting state, until the request is satisfied.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] Subsequent activations of the button between the initial activation and the request being satisfied have no effect, unless the system is designed to adjust the time for satisfying the request based on the number of activations.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] Similarly, the elevator "close" button may be pressed many times to the same effect as once, since the doors close on a fixed schedule – unless the "open" button is pressed.
[src:distributed-systems/idempotence] The "open" button is not idempotent, because each press adds further delay.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] The **Lamport timestamp** algorithm is a simple logical clock algorithm used to determine the order of events in a distributed computer system.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] As different nodes or processes will typically not be perfectly synchronized, this algorithm is used to provide a partial ordering of events with minimal overhead, and conceptually provide a starting point for the more advanced vector clock method.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] The algorithm is named after its creator, Leslie Lamport.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Distributed algorithms such as resource synchronization often depend on some method of ordering events to function.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] For example, consider a system with two processes and a disk.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] The processes send messages to each other, and also send messages to the disk requesting access.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] The disk grants access in the order the messages were *received*.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] For example process A sends a message to the disk requesting write access, and then sends a read instruction message to process B .
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Process B receives the message, and as a result sends its own read request message to the disk.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] A logical clock algorithm provides a mechanism to determine facts about the order of such events.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Note that if two events happen in different processes that do not exchange messages directly or indirectly via third-party processes, then we say that the two processes are concurrent, that is, nothing can be said about the ordering of the two events.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Lamport invented a simple mechanism by which the *happened-before* ordering can be captured numerically.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] A Lamport logical clock is a numerical software counter value maintained in each process.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Conceptually, this logical clock can be thought of as a clock that only has meaning in relation to messages moving between processes.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] When a process receives a message, it re-synchronizes its logical clock with that sender.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] The above-mentioned vector clock is a generalization of the idea into the context of an arbitrary number of parallel, independent processes.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] On receiving a message, the counter of the recipient is updated, if necessary, to the greater of its current counter and the timestamp in the received message.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] The counter is then incremented by 1 before the message is considered received.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] For every two different events a and b occurring in the same process, and $C(x)$ being the timestamp for a certain event x , it is necessary that $C(a)$ never equals $C(b)$ .
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] For any two events, a and b , if there is any way that a could have influenced b , then the Lamport timestamp of a will be less than the Lamport timestamp of b .
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] It’s also possible to have two events where we can’t say which came first; when that happens, it means that they couldn’t have affected each other.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] If a and b can’t have any effect on each other, then it doesn’t matter which one came first.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] A Lamport clock may be used to create a partial ordering of events between processes.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Given a logical clock following these rules, the following relation is true: if $a\rightarrow b$ then $C(a)<C(b)$ , where $\rightarrow \,$ means *happened-before*.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] This relation only goes one way, and is called the *clock consistency condition*: if one event comes before another, then that event's logical clock comes before the other's.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] The *strong clock consistency condition*, which is two way (if $C(a)<C(b)$ then $a\rightarrow b$ ), can be obtained by other techniques such as vector clocks.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Using only a simple Lamport clock, only a partial causal ordering can be inferred from the clock.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] However, via the contrapositive, it's true that $C(a)\nless C(b)$ implies $a\nrightarrow b$ .
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] So, for example, if $C(a)\geq C(b)$ then a cannot have *happened-before* b .
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Another way of putting this is that $C(a)<C(b)$ means that a may have *happened-before* b , or be incomparable with b in the *happened-before* ordering, but a did not happen after b .
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Nevertheless, Lamport timestamps can be used to create a total ordering of events in a distributed system by using some arbitrary mechanism to break ties (e.g., the ID of the process).
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] The caveat is that this ordering is artificial and cannot be depended on to imply a causal relationship.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] In a distributed system, it is not possible in practice to synchronize time across entities (typically thought of as processes) within the system; hence, the entities can use the concept of a logical clock based on the events through which they communicate.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] If two entities do not exchange any messages, then they probably do not need to share a common clock; events occurring on those entities are termed concurrent events.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Among the processes on the same local machine we can order the events based on the local clock of the system.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] When two entities communicate by message passing, then the send event is said to *happen-before* the receive event, and the logical order can be established among the events.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] A distributed system is said to have partial order if we can have a partial order relationship among the events in the system.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] If "totality", i.e., causal relationship among all events in the system, can be established, then the system is said to have total order.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] A single entity cannot have two events occur simultaneously.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] If the system has total order we can determine the order among all events in the system.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] If the system has partial order between processes, which is the type of order Lamport's logical clock provides, then we can only tell the ordering between entities that interact.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Lamport clocks lead to a situation where all events in a distributed system are totally ordered.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] That is, if $a\rightarrow b$ , then we can say a actually happened before b .
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Note that with Lamport’s clocks, nothing can be said about the actual time of a and b .
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] If the logical clock says $C(a)<C(b)$ , that does not mean in reality that a actually happened before b in terms of real time.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Lamport clocks show non-causality, but do not capture all causality.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Knowing $a\rightarrow c$ and $b\rightarrow c$ shows c did not cause a or b but we cannot say which initiated c .
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] This kind of information can be important when trying to replay events in a distributed system (such as when trying to recover after a crash).
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] If one node goes down, and we know the causal relationships between messages, then we can replay those messages and respect the causal relationship to get that node back up to the state it needs to be in.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] The happened-before relation captures potential causality, not true causality.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] In 2011–2012, Munindar Singh proposed a declarative, multiagent approach based on true causality called information protocols.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] An information protocol specifies the constraints on communications between the agents that constitute a distributed system.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] However, instead of specifying message ordering (e.g., via a state machine, a common way of representing protocols in computing), an information protocol specifies the information dependencies between the communications that agents (the protocol's endpoints) may send.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] An agent may send a communication in a local state (its communication history) only if the communication and the state together satisfy the relevant information dependencies.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] For example, an information protocol for an e-commerce application may specify that to send a quote with parameters ID (a uniquifier), item, and price, seller must already know the ID and item from its state but can generate whatever price it wants.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] A remarkable thing about information protocols is that although emissions are constrained, receptions are not.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Specifically, agents may receive communications in any order whatsoever – receptions simply bring information and there is no point delaying them.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] This means that information protocols can be enacted over unordered communication services such as UDP.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] The bigger idea is that of application semantics, the idea of designing distributed systems based on the content of the messages, an idea implicated in the end-to-end principle.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] Current approaches largely ignore semantics and focus on providing application-agnostic ("syntactic") message delivery and ordering guarantees in communication services, which is where ideas like potential causality help.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] But if we had a suitable way of doing application semantics, then we wouldn't need such communication services.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] An unordered, unreliable communication service would suffice.
[src:distributed-systems/lamport-timestamp] The real value of the information protocols approach is that it provides the foundations for an application semantics approach.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:distributed-systems/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The model is a specialization of the *split-apply-combine* strategy for data analysis.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] It is inspired by the map and reduce functions commonly used in functional programming, although their purpose in the MapReduce framework is not the same as in their original forms.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] As such, a single-threaded implementation of MapReduce is usually not faster than a traditional (non-MapReduce) implementation; any gains are usually only seen with multi-threaded implementations on multi-processor hardware.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The use of this model is beneficial only when the optimized distributed shuffle operation (which reduces network communication cost) and fault tolerance features of the MapReduce framework come into play.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Optimizing the communication cost is essential to a good MapReduce algorithm.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] MapReduce libraries have been written in many programming languages, with different levels of optimization.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] A popular open-source implementation that has support for distributed shuffles is part of Apache Hadoop.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The name MapReduce originally referred to the proprietary Google technology, but has since become a generic trademark.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] By 2014, Google was no longer using MapReduce as its primary *big data* processing model, and development on Apache Mahout had moved on to more capable and less disk-oriented mechanisms that incorporated full map and reduce capabilities.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Processing can occur on data stored either in a filesystem (unstructured) or in a database (structured).
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] MapReduce can take advantage of the locality of data, processing it near the place it is stored in order to minimize communication overhead.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] **Shuffle:** worker nodes redistribute data based on the output keys (produced by the `map` function), such that all data belonging to one key is located on the same worker node.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] **Reduce:** worker nodes now process each group of output data, per key, in parallel.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] MapReduce allows for the distributed processing of the map and reduction operations.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Maps can be performed in parallel, provided that each mapping operation is independent of the others; in practice, this is limited by the number of independent data sources and/or the number of CPUs near each source.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Similarly, a set of 'reducers' can perform the reduction phase, provided that all outputs of the map operation that share the same key are presented to the same reducer at the same time, or that the reduction function is associative.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The parallelism also offers some possibility of recovering from partial failure of servers or storage during the operation: if one mapper or reducer fails, the work can be rescheduled – assuming the input data are still available.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] **Run the user-provided Map() code** – Map() is run exactly once for each *K1* key, generating output organized by key *K2*.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] **"Shuffle" the Map output to the Reduce processors** – the MapReduce system designates Reduce processors, assigns the *K2* key each processor should work on, and provides that processor with all the Map-generated data associated with that key.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] **Run the user-provided Reduce() code** – Reduce() is run exactly once for each *K2* key produced by the Map step.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] **Produce the final output** – the MapReduce system collects all the Reduce output, and sorts it by *K2* to produce the final outcome.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] These five steps can be logically thought of as running in sequence – each step starts only after the previous step is completed – although in practice they can be interleaved as long as the final result is not affected.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] In many situations, the input data might have already been distributed ("sharded") among many different servers, in which case step 1 could sometimes be greatly simplified by assigning Map servers that would process the locally present input data.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Similarly, step 3 could sometimes be sped up by assigning Reduce processors that are as close as possible to the Map-generated data they need to process.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The *Map* and *Reduce* functions of *MapReduce* are both defined with respect to data structured in (key, value) pairs.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The *Map* function is applied in parallel to every pair (keyed by `k1`) in the input dataset.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] This produces a list of pairs (keyed by `k2`) for each call.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] After that, the MapReduce framework collects all pairs with the same key (`k2`) from all lists and groups them together, creating one group for each key.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Each *Reduce* call typically produces either one key value pair or an empty return, though one call is allowed to return more than one key value pair.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The returns of all calls are collected as the desired result list.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Thus the MapReduce framework transforms a list of (key, value) pairs into another list of (key, value) pairs.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] This behavior is different from the typical functional programming map and reduce combination, which accepts a list of arbitrary values and returns one single value that combines *all* the values returned by map.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] It is necessary but not sufficient to have implementations of the map and reduce abstractions in order to implement MapReduce.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Distributed implementations of MapReduce require a means of connecting the processes performing the Map and Reduce phases.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Other options are possible, such as direct streaming from mappers to reducers, or for the mapping processors to serve up their results to reducers that query them.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Here, each document is split into words, and each word is counted by the *map* function, using the word as the result key.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The framework puts together all the pairs with the same key and feeds them to the same call to *reduce*.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Thus, this function just needs to sum all of its input values to find the total appearances of that word.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] As another example, imagine that for a database of 1.1 billion people, one would like to compute the average number of social contacts a person has according to age.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Note that in the Reduce function, C is the count of people having in total N contacts, so in the Map function it is natural to write C=1, since every output pair is referring to the contacts of one single person.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The MapReduce system would line up the 1100 Map processors, and would provide each with its corresponding 1 million input records.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The Map step would produce 1.1 billion (Y,(N,1)) records, with Y values ranging between, say, 8 and 103.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The MapReduce System would then line up the 96 Reduce processors by performing shuffling operation of the key/value pairs due to the fact that we need average per age, and provide each with its millions of corresponding input records.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The Reduce step would result in the much reduced set of only 96 output records (Y,A), which would be put in the final result file, sorted by Y.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The count info in the record is important if the processing is reduced more than one time.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] If we reduce it with file #3, we lose the count of how many records we've already seen, so we end up with an average of 9.5 contacts for a 10-year-old person ((9+10)/2), which is wrong.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Software framework architecture adheres to open-closed principle where code is effectively divided into unmodifiable *frozen spots* and extensible *hot spots*.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The frozen spot of the MapReduce framework is a large distributed sort.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The *input reader* divides the input into appropriate size 'splits' (in practice, typically, 64 MB to 128 MB) and the framework assigns one split to each *Map* function.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The *input reader* reads data from stable storage (typically, a distributed file system) and generates key/value pairs.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] A common example will read a directory full of text files and return each line as a record.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The *Map* function takes a series of key/value pairs, processes each, and generates zero or more output key/value pairs.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The input and output types of the map can be (and often are) different from each other.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] If the application is doing a word count, the map function would break the line into words and output a key/value pair for each word.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Each output pair would contain the word as the key and the number of instances of that word in the line as the value.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Each *Map* function output is allocated to a particular *reducer* by the application's *partition* function for sharding purposes.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The *partition* function is given the key and the number of reducers and returns the index of the desired *reducer*.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] A typical default is to hash the key and use the hash value modulo the number of *reducers*.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Between the map and reduce stages, the data are *shuffled* (parallel-sorted / exchanged between nodes) in order to move the data from the map node that produced them to the shard in which they will be reduced.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The shuffle can sometimes take longer than the computation time depending on network bandwidth, CPU speeds, data produced and time taken by map and reduce computations.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The input for each *Reduce* is pulled from the machine where the *Map* ran and sorted using the application's *comparison* function.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The framework calls the application's *Reduce* function once for each unique key in the sorted order.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The *Reduce* can iterate through the values that are associated with that key and produce zero or more outputs.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] In the word count example, the *Reduce* function takes the input values, sums them and generates a single output of the word and the final sum.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The *Output Writer* writes the output of the *Reduce* to the stable storage.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Properties of monoids are the basis for ensuring the validity of MapReduce operations.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] In the Algebird package a Scala implementation of Map/Reduce explicitly requires a monoid class type .
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The operations of MapReduce deal with two types: the type *A* of input data being mapped, and the type *B* of output data being reduced.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The *Map* operation takes individual values of type *A* and produces, for each *a:A* a value *b:B*; The *Reduce* operation requires a binary operation • defined on values of type *B*; it consists of folding all available *b:B* to a single value.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] From a basic requirements point of view, any MapReduce operation must involve the ability to arbitrarily regroup data being reduced.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The second property guarantees that, when parallelized over multiple nodes, the nodes that don't have any data to process would have no impact on the result.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] These two properties amount to having a monoid (*B*, •, *e*) on values of type *B* with operation • and with neutral element *e*.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] There's no requirements on the values of type *A*; an arbitrary function *A* → *B* can be used for the *Map* operation.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] This means that we have a catamorphism *A** → (*B*, •, *e*).
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Here *A** denotes a Kleene star, also known as the type of lists over *A*.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The *Shuffle* operation per se is not related to the essence of MapReduce; it's needed to distribute calculations over the cloud.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] It follows from the above that not every binary *Reduce* operation will work in MapReduce.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] MapReduce programs are not guaranteed to be fast.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The main benefit of this programming model is to exploit the optimized shuffle operation of the platform, and only having to write the *Map* and *Reduce* parts of the program.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] In practice, the author of a MapReduce program however has to take the shuffle step into consideration; in particular the partition function and the amount of data written by the *Map* function can have a large impact on the performance and scalability.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Additional modules such as the *Combiner* function can help to reduce the amount of data written to disk, and transmitted over the network.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] MapReduce applications can achieve sub-linear speedups under specific circumstances.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] When designing a MapReduce algorithm, the author needs to choose a good tradeoff between the computation and the communication costs.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Communication cost often dominates the computation cost, and many MapReduce implementations are designed to write all communication to distributed storage for crash recovery.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] In tuning performance of MapReduce, the complexity of mapping, shuffle, sorting (grouping by the key), and reducing has to be taken into account.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The amount of data produced by the mappers is a key parameter that shifts the bulk of the computation cost between mapping and reducing.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Reducing includes sorting (grouping of the keys) which has nonlinear complexity.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Hence, small partition sizes reduce sorting time, but there is a trade-off because having a large number of reducers may be impractical.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The influence of split unit size is marginal (unless chosen particularly badly, say <1MB).
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The gains from some mappers reading load from local disks, on average, is minor.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] For processes that complete quickly, and where the data fits into main memory of a single machine or a small cluster, using a MapReduce framework usually is not effective.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Since these frameworks are designed to recover from the loss of whole nodes during the computation, they write interim results to distributed storage.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] This crash recovery is expensive, and only pays off when the computation involves many computers and a long runtime of the computation.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] A task that completes in seconds can just be restarted in the case of an error, and the likelihood of at least one machine failing grows quickly with the cluster size.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] On such problems, implementations keeping all data in memory and simply restarting a computation on node failures or —when the data is small enough— non-distributed solutions will often be faster than a MapReduce system.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] MapReduce achieves reliability by parceling out a number of operations on the set of data to each node in the network.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Each node is expected to report back periodically with completed work and status updates.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] If a node falls silent for longer than that interval, the master node (similar to the master server in the Google File System) records the node as dead and sends out the node's assigned work to other nodes.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Individual operations use atomic operations for naming file outputs as a check to ensure that there are not parallel conflicting threads running.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] When files are renamed, it is possible to also copy them to another name in addition to the name of the task (allowing for side-effects).
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The reduce operations operate much the same way.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Because of their inferior properties with regard to parallel operations, the master node attempts to schedule reduce operations on the same node, or in the same rack as the node holding the data being operated on.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] This property is desirable as it conserves bandwidth across the backbone network of the datacenter.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Implementations are not necessarily highly reliable.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] For example, in older versions of Hadoop the *NameNode* was a single point of failure for the distributed filesystem.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Moreover, the MapReduce model has been adapted to several computing environments like multi-core and many-core systems, desktop grids, multi-cluster, volunteer computing environments, dynamic cloud environments, mobile environments, and high-performance computing environments.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] At Google, MapReduce was used to completely regenerate Google's index of the World Wide Web.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] It replaced the old *ad hoc* programs that updated the index and ran the various analyses.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Development at Google has since moved on to technologies such as Percolator, FlumeJava and MillWheel that offer streaming operation and updates instead of batch processing, to allow integrating "live" search results without rebuilding the complete index.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] MapReduce's stable inputs and outputs are usually stored in a distributed file system.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The transient data are usually stored on local disk and fetched remotely by the reducers.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] David DeWitt and Michael Stonebraker, computer scientists specializing in parallel databases and shared-nothing architectures, have been critical of the breadth of problems that MapReduce can be used for.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] They called its interface too low-level and questioned whether it really represents the paradigm shift its proponents have claimed it is.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] They challenged the MapReduce proponents' claims of novelty, citing Teradata as an example of prior art that has existed for over two decades.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Greg Jorgensen wrote an article rejecting these views.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] Jorgensen asserts that DeWitt and Stonebraker's entire analysis is groundless as MapReduce was never designed nor intended to be used as a database.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] DeWitt and Stonebraker have subsequently published a detailed benchmark study in 2009 comparing performance of Hadoop's MapReduce and RDBMS approaches on several specific problems.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] They concluded that relational databases offer real advantages for many kinds of data use, especially on complex processing or where the data is used across an enterprise, but that MapReduce may be easier for users to adopt for simple or one-time processing tasks.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The MapReduce programming paradigm was also described in Danny Hillis's 1985 thesis intended for use on the Connection Machine, where it was called "xapping/reduction" and relied upon that machine's special hardware to accelerate both map and reduce.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The dialect ultimately used for the Connection Machine, the 1986 StarLisp, had parallel `*map` and `reduce!!`, which in turn was based on the 1984 Common Lisp, which had non-parallel `map` and `reduce` built in.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The tree-like approach that the Connection Machine's hypercube architecture uses to execute `reduce` in $O(\log n)$ time is effectively the same as the approach referred to within the Google paper as prior work.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] In 2010 Google was granted what is described as a patent on MapReduce.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The patent, filed in 2004, may cover use of MapReduce by open source software such as Hadoop, CouchDB, and others.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] In *Ars Technica*, an editor acknowledged Google's role in popularizing the MapReduce concept, but questioned whether the patent was valid or novel.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] In 2013, as part of its "Open Patent Non-Assertion (OPN) Pledge", Google pledged to only use the patent defensively.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] The patent is expected to expire on 23 December 2026.
[src:distributed-systems/mapreduce] MapReduce tasks must be written as acyclic dataflow programs, i.e. a stateless mapper followed by a stateless reducer, that are executed by a batch job scheduler.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Replication in space or in time is often linked to scheduling algorithms.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Access to a replicated entity is typically uniform with access to a single non-replicated entity.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] The replication itself should be transparent to an external user.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] In a failure scenario, a failover of replicas should be hidden as much as possible with respect to quality of service.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] When one leader replica is designated via leader election to process all the requests, the system is using a primary-backup or primary-replica scheme, which is predominant in high-availability clusters.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] In comparison, if any replica can process a request and distribute a new state, the system is using a multi-primary or multi-master scheme.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] In the latter case, some form of distributed concurrency control must be used, such as a distributed lock manager.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Load balancing differs from task replication, since it distributes a load of different computations across machines, and allows a single computation to be dropped in case of failure.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Load balancing, however, sometimes uses data replication (especially multi-master replication) internally, to distribute its data among machines.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Backup differs from replication in that the saved copy of data remains unchanged for a long period of time.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Replicas, on the other hand, undergo frequent updates and quickly lose any historical state.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Replication is one of the oldest and most important topics in the overall area of distributed systems.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Data replication and computation replication both require processes to handle incoming events.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Processes for data replication are passive and operate only to maintain the stored data, reply to read requests and apply updates.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Computation replication is usually performed to provide fault-tolerance, and take over an operation if one component fails.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] In both cases, the underlying needs are to ensure that the replicas see the same events in equivalent orders, so that they stay in consistent states and any replica can respond to queries.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Database replication involves maintaining copies of the same data on multiple machines, typically implemented through three main approaches: single-leader, multi-leader, and leaderless replication.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] In single-leader (also called primary/replica) replication, one database instance is designated as the leader (primary), which handles all write operations.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] The leader logs these updates, which then propagate to replica nodes.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Each replica acknowledges receipt of updates, enabling subsequent write operations.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Replicas primarily serve read requests, though they may serve stale data due to replication lag – the delay in propagating changes from the leader.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] In multi-master replication (also called multi-leader), updates can be submitted to any database node, which then propagate to other servers.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] This approach is particularly beneficial in multi-data center deployments, where it enables local write processing while masking inter-data center network latency.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] However, it introduces substantially increased costs and complexity which may make it impractical in some situations.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] The most common challenge that exists in multi-master replication is transactional conflict prevention or resolution when concurrent modifications occur on different leader nodes.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Most synchronous (or eager) replication solutions perform conflict prevention, while asynchronous (or lazy) solutions have to perform conflict resolution.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] For instance, if the same record is changed on two nodes simultaneously, an eager replication system would detect the conflict before confirming the commit and abort one of the transactions.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] A lazy replication system would allow both transactions to commit and run a conflict resolution during re-synchronization.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Conflict resolution methods can include techniques like last-write-wins, application-specific logic, or merging concurrent updates.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] However, replication transparency can not always be achieved.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] When data is replicated in a database, they will be constrained by CAP theorem or PACELC theorem.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] In the NoSQL movement, data consistency is usually sacrificed in exchange for other more desired properties, such as availability (A), partition tolerance (P), etc.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Various data consistency models have also been developed to serve as Service Level Agreement (SLA) between service providers and the users.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Active (real-time) storage replication is usually implemented by distributing updates of a block device to several physical hard disks.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] This way, any file system supported by the operating system can be replicated without modification, as the file system code works on a level above the block device driver layer.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] It is implemented either in hardware (in a disk array controller) or in software (in a device driver).
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] The most basic method is disk mirroring, which is typical for locally connected disks.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] The storage industry narrows the definitions, so *mirroring* is a local (short-distance) operation.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] A replication is extendable across a computer network, so that the disks can be located in physically distant locations, and the primary/replica database replication model is usually applied.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] The purpose of replication is to prevent damage from failures or disasters that may occur in one location – or in case such events do occur, to improve the ability to recover data.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] For replication, latency is the key factor because it determines either how far apart the sites can be or the type of replication that can be employed.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] The main characteristic of such cross-site replication is how write operations are handled, through either asynchronous or synchronous replication; synchronous replication needs to wait for the destination server's response in any write operation whereas asynchronous replication does not.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Synchronous replication guarantees "zero data loss" by the means of atomic write operations, where the write operation is not considered complete until acknowledged by both the local and remote storage.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Most applications wait for a write transaction to complete before proceeding with further work, hence overall performance decreases considerably.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Inherently, performance drops proportionally to distance, as minimum latency is dictated by the speed of light.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] For 10 km distance, the fastest possible roundtrip takes 67 μs, whereas an entire local cached write completes in about 10–20 μs.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] In asynchronous replication, the write operation is considered complete as soon as local storage acknowledges it.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Remote storage is updated with a small lag.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Performance is greatly increased, but in case of a local storage failure, the remote storage is not guaranteed to have the current copy of data (the most recent data may be lost).
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Semi-synchronous replication typically considers a write operation complete when acknowledged by local storage and received or logged by the remote server.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] The actual remote write is performed asynchronously, resulting in better performance but remote storage will lag behind the local storage, so that there is no guarantee of durability (i.e., seamless transparency) in the case of local storage failure.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Point-in-time replication produces periodic snapshots which are replicated instead of primary storage.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] This is intended to replicate only the changed data instead of the entire volume.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] As less information is replicated using this method, replication can occur over less-expensive bandwidth links such as iSCSI or T1 instead of fiberoptic lines.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Many distributed filesystems use replication to ensure fault tolerance and avoid a single point of failure.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Many commercial synchronous replication systems do not freeze when the remote replica fails or loses connection – behaviour which guarantees zero data loss – but proceed to operate locally, losing the desired zero recovery point objective.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Techniques of wide-area network (WAN) optimization can be applied to address the limits imposed by latency.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] File-based replication conducts data replication at the logical level (i.e., individual data files) rather than at the storage block level.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] There are many different ways of performing this, which almost exclusively rely on software.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] A kernel driver (specifically a filter driver) can be used to intercept calls to the filesystem functions, capturing any activity as it occurs.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] This uses the same type of technology that real-time active virus checkers employ.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] At this level, logical file operations are captured like file open, write, delete, etc.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] The kernel driver transmits these commands to another process, generally over a network to a different machine, which will mimic the operations of the source machine.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Like block-level storage replication, the file-level replication allows both synchronous and asynchronous modes.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] In synchronous mode, write operations on the source machine are held and not allowed to occur until the destination machine has acknowledged the successful replication.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Synchronous mode is less common with file replication products although a few solutions exist.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] File-level replication solutions allow for informed decisions about replication based on the location and type of the file.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] For example, temporary files or parts of a filesystem that hold no business value could be excluded.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] The data transmitted can also be more granular; if an application writes 100 bytes, only the 100 bytes are transmitted instead of a complete disk block (generally 4,096 bytes).
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] This substantially reduces the amount of data sent from the source machine and the storage burden on the destination machine.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Drawbacks of this software-only solution include the requirement for implementation and maintenance on the operating system level, and an increased burden on the machine's processing power.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Similarly to database transaction logs, many file systems have the ability to journal their activity.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] The journal can be sent to another machine, either periodically or in real time by streaming.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] On the replica side, the journal can be used to play back file system modifications.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] One of the notable implementations is Microsoft's System Center Data Protection Manager (DPM), released in 2005, which performs periodic updates but does not offer real-time replication.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] This is the process of comparing the source and destination file systems and ensuring that the destination matches the source.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] The key benefit is that such solutions are generally free or inexpensive.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] The downside is that the process of synchronizing them is quite system-intensive, and consequently this process generally runs infrequently.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] One of the notable implementations is rsync.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] In a paging operating system, pages in a paging file are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] In IBM's VSAM, index data are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Another example of using replication appears in distributed shared memory systems, where many nodes of the system share the same page of memory.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] This usually means that each node has a separate copy (replica) of a specific page.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Many classical approaches to replication are based on a primary-backup model where one device or process has unilateral control over one or more other processes or devices.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] For example, the primary might perform some computation, streaming a log of updates to a backup (standby) process, which can then take over if the primary fails.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] This approach is common for replicating databases, despite the risk that if a portion of the log is lost during a failure, the backup might not be in a state identical to the primary, and transactions could then be lost.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] A weakness of primary-backup schemes is that only one is actually performing operations.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Fault-tolerance is gained, but the identical backup system doubles the costs.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] 1985, the distributed systems research community began to explore alternative methods of replicating data.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] An outgrowth of this work was the emergence of schemes in which a group of replicas could cooperate, with each process acting as a backup while also handling a share of the workload.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Computer scientist Jim Gray analyzed multi-primary replication schemes under the transactional model and published a widely cited paper skeptical of the approach "The Dangers of Replication and a Solution".
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] He argued that unless the data splits in some natural way so that the database can be treated as *n* disjoint sub-databases, concurrency control conflicts will result in seriously degraded performance and the group of replicas will probably slow as a function of *n*.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Gray suggested that the most common approaches are likely to result in degradation that scales as *O(n³)*.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] His solution, which is to partition the data, is only viable in situations where data actually has a natural partitioning key.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] In the 1985–1987, the virtual synchrony model was proposed and emerged as a widely adopted standard (it was used in the Isis Toolkit, Horus, Transis, Ensemble, Totem, Spread, C-Ensemble, Phoenix and Quicksilver systems, and is the basis for the CORBA fault-tolerant computing standard).
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Virtual synchrony permits a multi-primary approach in which a group of processes cooperates to parallelize some aspects of request processing.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] The scheme can only be used for some forms of in-memory data, but can provide linear speedups in the size of the group.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] A number of modern products support similar schemes.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] For example, the Spread Toolkit supports this same virtual synchrony model and can be used to implement a multi-primary replication scheme; it would also be possible to use C-Ensemble or Quicksilver in this manner.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] WANdisco permits active replication where every node on a network is an exact copy or replica and hence every node on the network is active at one time; this scheme is optimized for use in a wide area network (WAN).
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Modern multi-primary replication protocols optimize for the common failure-free operation.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] Chain replication is a popular family of such protocols.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] State-of-the-art protocol variants of chain replication offer high throughput and strong consistency by arranging replicas in a chain for writes.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] This approach enables local reads on all replica nodes but has high latency for writes that must traverse multiple nodes sequentially.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] A more recent multi-primary protocol, Hermes, combines cache-coherent-inspired invalidations and logical timestamps to achieve strong consistency with local reads and high-performance writes from all replicas.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] During fault-free operation, its broadcast-based writes are non-conflicting and commit after just one multicast round-trip to replica nodes.
[src:distributed-systems/replication-computing] This design results in high throughput and low latency for both reads and writes.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] In transaction processing, databases, and computer networking, the **two-phase commit protocol** (**2PC**, *tupac*) is a type of atomic commitment protocol (ACP).
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] It is a distributed algorithm that coordinates all the processes that participate in a distributed atomic transaction on whether to commit or abort (roll back) the transaction.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] This protocol (a specialised type of consensus protocol) achieves its goal even in many cases of temporary system failure (involving either process, network node, communication, etc. failures), and is thus widely used.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] However, it is not resilient to all possible failure configurations, and in rare cases, manual intervention is needed to remedy an outcome.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] To accommodate recovery from failure (automatic in most cases) the protocol's participants use logging of the protocol's states.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] Log records, which are typically slow to generate but survive failures, are used by the protocol's recovery procedures.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] Many protocol variants exist that primarily differ in logging strategies and recovery mechanisms.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] Though usually intended to be used infrequently, recovery procedures compose a substantial portion of the protocol, due to many possible failure scenarios to be considered and supported by the protocol.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The commit phase, in which, based on voting of the participants, the coordinator decides whether to commit (only if all have voted "Yes") or abort the transaction (otherwise), and notifies the result to all the participants.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The participants then follow with the needed actions (commit or abort) with their local transactional resources (also called recoverable resources; e.g., database data) and their respective portions in the transaction's other output (if applicable).
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The two-phase commit (2PC) protocol should not be confused with the two-phase locking (2PL) protocol, a concurrency control protocol.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The protocol works in the following manner: one node is a designated coordinator, which is the master site, and the rest of the nodes in the network are designated the participants.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] 4. any two nodes can communicate with each other.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The last assumption is not too restrictive, as network communication can typically be rerouted.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The first two assumptions are much stronger; if a node is totally destroyed then data can be lost.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The protocol is initiated by the coordinator after the last step of the transaction has been reached.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The participants then respond with an agreement message or an abort message depending on whether the transaction has been processed successfully at the participant.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The participants execute the transaction up to the point where they will be asked to commit.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] They each write an entry to their undo log and an entry to their redo log.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] (participant votes No to commit), if the participant experiences a failure that will make it impossible to commit.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] Each participant completes the operation, and releases all the locks and resources held during the transaction.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] Each participant sends an acknowledgement to the coordinator.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The coordinator completes the transaction when all acknowledgements have been received.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] Each participant undoes the transaction using the undo log, and releases the resources and locks held during the transaction.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The coordinator undoes the transaction when all acknowledgements have been received.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] An * next to the record type means that the record is forced to stable storage.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] If the coordinator fails permanently, some participants will never resolve their transactions: After a participant has sent an agreement message as a response to the commit-request message from the coordinator, it will block until a commit or rollback is received.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] A two-phase commit protocol cannot dependably recover from a failure of both the coordinator and a cohort member during the commit phase.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] If only the coordinator had failed, and no cohort members had received a commit message, it could safely be inferred that no commit had happened.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] If, however, both the coordinator and a cohort member failed, it is possible that the failed cohort member was the first to be notified, and had actually done the commit.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] Even if a new coordinator is selected, it cannot confidently proceed with the operation until it has received an agreement from all cohort members, and hence must block until all cohort members respond.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] In many cases the 2PC protocol is distributed in a computer network.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The databases involved with a distributed transaction, the participants, both the coordinator and participants, register to close TMs (typically residing on respective same network nodes as the participants) for terminating that transaction using 2PC.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] Each distributed transaction has an ad hoc set of TMs, the TMs to which the transaction participants register.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] A leader, the coordinator TM, exists for each transaction to coordinate 2PC for it, typically the TM of the coordinator database.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] However, the coordinator role can be transferred to another TM for performance or reliability reasons.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] Rather than exchanging 2PC messages among themselves, the participants exchange the messages with their respective TMs.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The relevant TMs communicate among themselves to execute the 2PC protocol schema above, "representing" the respective participants, for terminating that transaction.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] With this architecture the protocol is fully distributed (does not need any central processing component or data structure), and scales up with number of network nodes (network size) effectively.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] This common architecture is also effective for the distribution of other atomic commitment protocols besides 2PC, since all such protocols use the same voting mechanism and outcome propagation to protocol participants.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] Database research has been done on ways to get most of the benefits of the two-phase commit protocol while reducing costs by protocol optimizations and protocol operations saving under certain system's behavior assumptions.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] Presumed abort or Presumed commit are common such optimizations.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] An assumption about the outcome of transactions, either commit, or abort, can save both messages and logging operations by the participants during the 2PC protocol's execution.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] For example, when presumed abort, if during system recovery from failure no logged evidence for commit of some transaction is found by the recovery procedure, then it assumes that the transaction has been aborted, and acts accordingly.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] This means that it does not matter if aborts are logged at all, and such logging can be saved under this assumption.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] Typically a penalty of additional operations is paid during recovery from failure, depending on optimization type.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] Thus the best variant of optimization, if any, is chosen according to failure and transaction outcome statistics.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The Tree 2PC protocol (also called Nested 2PC, or Recursive 2PC) is a common variant of 2PC in a computer network, which better utilizes the underlying communication infrastructure.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The participants in a distributed transaction are typically invoked in an order which defines a tree structure, the invocation tree, where the participants are the nodes and the edges are the invocations (communication links).
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The same tree is commonly utilized to complete the transaction by a 2PC protocol, but also another communication tree can be utilized for this, in principle.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] In a tree 2PC the coordinator is considered the root ("top") of a communication tree (inverted tree), while the participants are the other nodes.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The coordinator can be the node that originated the transaction (invoked recursively (transitively) the other participants), but also another node in the same tree can take the coordinator role instead.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The Dynamic two-phase commit (Dynamic two-phase commitment, D2PC) protocol is a variant of Tree 2PC with no predetermined coordinator.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] It subsumes several optimizations that have been proposed earlier.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] Agreement messages (Yes votes) start to propagate from all the leaves, each leaf when completing its tasks on behalf of the transaction (becoming ready).
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] An intermediate (non leaf) node sends ready when an agreement message to the last (single) neighboring node from which agreement message has not yet been received.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] The coordinator is determined dynamically by racing agreement messages over the transaction tree, at the place where they collide.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] They collide either at a transaction tree node, to be the coordinator, or on a tree edge.
[src:distributed-systems/two-phase-commit-protocol] In the latter case one of the two edge's nodes is elected as a coordinator (any node).
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] A **vector clock** is a data structure used for determining the partial ordering of events in a distributed system and detecting causality violations.
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] Just as in Lamport timestamps, inter-process messages contain the state of the sending process's logical clock.
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] A vector clock of a system of *n* processes is a vector (equivalentlly, a 1-dimensional array) of *n* logical clocks, one clock per process.
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] Besides maintaining its own clock, every process also keeps track of the largest value of each of the other processes' clocks that it has so far been informed of.
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] Lamport originated the idea of logical Lamport clocks in 1978.
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] However, the logical clocks in that paper were scalars, not vectors.
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] The generalization to vector time was developed several times, apparently independently, by different authors in the early 1980s.
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] The papers canonically cited in reference to vector clocks are Colin Fidge’s and Friedemann Mattern’s 1988 works, as they (independently) established the name "vector clock" and the mathematical properties of vector clocks.
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] Vector clocks allow for the partial causal ordering of events.
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] Vector clocks can reliably detect causality in distributed systems subject to crash failures.
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] However, when processes behave arbitrarily or maliciously—as in the Byzantine failure model—causality detection becomes fundamentally impossible , rendering vector clocks ineffective in such environments.
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] This impossibility result holds for all variants of vector clocks, as it stems from core limitations inherent to the problem of causality detection under Byzantine faults.
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] Modern distributed systems utilize variations of vector clocks to enforce causal ordering of transactions without relying on a central wall-clock time.
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] For instance, the Cerberus protocol uses logical clocks to track the state "version" of each shard.
[src:distributed-systems/vector-clock] When a transaction spans multiple shards, the vector of these logical clocks allows the network to validate that the transaction is interacting with the most current state of all involved assets, enabling atomic composability in an adversarial environment.
